// Semantic direction:
// fysikk_verden integrates all rigidbodies using a sub-step approach for stability.
// fv_iterasjoner controls how many constraint resolution passes occur per frame.
// rigidbody carries the physical state: position, velocity, angle, angular velocity.
// rb_statisk never moves; rb_kinematisk moves by user control without physics forces.
// rb_apply_kraft applies a continuous force (like gravity); rb_apply_impuls applies an instant impulse.
// kollisjonsform describes the shape used for collision detection; kf_komposittt combines multiple shapes.
// aabb (Axis-Aligned Bounding Box) is the cheapest broad-phase test.
// sat_test (Separating Axis Theorem) detects collision between convex polygons.
// gjennomtrenging is the overlap depth; normal_vektor is the separation direction.
// impulsmethode resolves collisions by computing and applying corrective impulses.
// restitusjon is the bounciness coefficient: 0 = perfectly inelastic, 1 = perfectly elastic.
// trigger is a non-physical shape that fires callbacks when other bodies enter or leave it.
// rutenett_spatial divides the world into cells; objects are only tested against nearby cells.
// quadtree recursively subdivides space; qt_query_aabb returns all objects in a rectangle.
// bvh (Bounding Volume Hierarchy) provides efficient broad-phase for many dynamic objects.
// stråle is a directed ray; raycast returns the closest hit with its point, normal, and distance.

// Primitive flow:
// fv_oppdater: for each rigidbody: apply tyngdekraft → integrate velocity → integrate position
//   broad phase: rutenett_spatial or bvh → candidate pairs
//   narrow phase: sat_test or circle_circle → kontaktpunkt + gjennomtrenging
//   resolution: impulsmethode → update velocities
// trigger: check trigger_form overlaps → fire enter/exit/opphold callbacks
// raycast: stråle gjennom bvh → narrow phase each candidate → return nærmeste treff

// This defines 2D physics: rigid bodies, shapes, collision detection (SAT, circles,
// AABBs), impulse resolution, triggers, spatial partitioning, and raycasting.
